n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 23,146\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 308,116\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.9\n|-\n| [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 5,425\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 6,552,751\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 82.6\n|-\n| [[Roman Catholicism in Bulgaria|Roman Catholic]] Christians\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2,561\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 43,811\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.6\n|-\n| [[Protestantism in Bulgaria|Protestant]] Christians\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2,066\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 42,308\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.5\n|-\n| Others\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 442\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 14,937\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.2\n|-\n| Total population\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''746,664'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 100.0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''7,928,901'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 100.0\n|- style=\"background:#e0e0e0;\"\n|colspan=5|<small>Source: '''2001''' census</small>:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nsi.bg/Census/StrReligion.htm | title = Structure of the population by confession | publisher = NSI | access-date = 14 May 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091225163107/http://www.nsi.bg/Census/StrReligion.htm | archive-date = 25 December 2009 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nccedi.government.bg/page.php?category=92&id=247 | title = Ethnic minority communities | publisher = NSI | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170824222635/http://www.nccedi.government.bg/page.php?category=92&id=247 | archivedate = 24 August 2017 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Language===\n[[File:Bulgaria ethnic map.png|thumb|Distribution of the mother tongues by municipalities according to the 2011 census in Bulgaria]]\nA table showing the results of the '''2001''' census in Bulgaria regarding linguistic self-identification:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''The Turkish population in Bulgaria by mother tongue'''\n|- style=\"background:#e0e0e0;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Mother tongue\n! colspan=\"2\" | Speakers from the Turkish population\n! colspan=\"2\" | Speakers from the total population\n|- style=\"background:#e0e0e0;\"\n! Number\n! %\n! Number\n! %\n|-\n| [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 720,136\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 96.4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 762,516\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 9.6\n|-\n| [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 26,147\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 3.5\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 6,697,158\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 84.5\n|-\n| Others and unspecified\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 381\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 469,227\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 5.9\n|-\n| Total population\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''746,664'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 100.0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''7,928,901'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 100.0\n|- style=\"background:#e0e0e0;\"\n|colspan=5|<small>Source: '''2001''' census</small>:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nsi.bg/Census/MotherTongue.htm | title = Population by mother tongue | publisher = NSI | access-date = 15 May 2012 | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6Hy3ZXgwF?url=http://www.nsi.bg/Census/MotherTongue.htm | archive-date = 8 July 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Country Profile: Bulgaria|url=http://www.culturalpolicies.net/down/bulgaria_122011.pdf|work=Compendium of Cultural Policies and Trends in Europe, 13th edition|publisher=Council of Europe|accessdate=14 January 2013|year=2012}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Age structure ===\nThe Turkish population is composed of a slightly larger proportion of young people under twenty years old compared to the Bulgarian population.<ref>[http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120602032148/http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |date=2 June 2012 }} [http://www.nsi.bg/bg/content/3078/%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5-%D0%BF%D0%BE-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B8-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%89%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%BC%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B0-%D0%B8-%D0%B2%D1%8A%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82-%D0%BA%D1%8A%D0%BC-01022011-%D0%B3]</ref> Despite the fact that ethnic Turks constitute only 8 percent of the total population, they form 9.7 percent of all people under twenty years old and just 5 percent among all people that are aged sixty years or over.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"400px\"\n!colspan=19 | Population by age groups as of February 2011 by ethnic groups \n|-\n| Ethnic group || Total || 0\u20139 || 10\u201319 || 20\u201329 || 30\u201339 || 40\u201349 || 50\u201359 || 60\u201369 || 70\u201379 || 80+\n|-\n| [[Bulgarians]] || 5.664.624 || 408.927 || 472.704 || 710.717 || 825.784 || 786.593 || 833.007 || 802.613 || 559.323 || 264.956\n|-\n| '''Turks''' || '''588.318''' || '''59.719''' || '''71.901''' || '''89.602''' || '''91.343''' || '''85.903''' || '''80.054''' || '''62.534''' || '''35.454''' || '''11.808'''\n|-\n| [[Roma in Bulgaria|Roma]] || 325.343 || 67.568 || 59.511 || 59.442 || 49.572 || 37.723 || 28.411 || 15.833 || 6.031 || 1.252\n|-\n| Total || 7.364.570|| 659.806 ||693.051 || 979.895 || 1.079.277 || 1.009.486|| 1.040.678 || 956.411 || 647.178 || 298.788\n|}\n\n==Bulgarian Turkish literature==\n{{cleanup|section|date=June 2010}}\nBulgarian Turks have produced perhaps the most substantial amount of literature in the Turkish language outside Turkey. The list of noted writers includes: A\u015f\u0131k H\u0131fzi, H\u00fcseyin Raci Efendi, Ali Osman Ayrantok, Mehmet M\u00fczekka Con, \u0130zzet Din\u00e7, Mustafa Serit Alyanak, Muharrem Yumuk Mehmet, Beh\u00e7et Perim, Ali Kemal Balkanl\u0131, L\u00fctfi Er\u00e7in, Osman Kesiko\u011flu, Mehmet Fikri, O\u011fuz Peltek, Mehmet Muradov, Selim Bilalov, Osman K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7, Riza Mollov, Mustafa Kahveciev, Nuri Turgut Adal\u0131, Yusuf Kerimov, Kemal Bunarciev, Salih Baklac\u0131ev, S\u00fcleyman Gavazov, Hasan Karah\u00fcseyinov, Sabri Tatov, Ahmet Timisev, H\u00fcseyin O\u011fuz, Ahmet \u015eerifov, M\u00fclazim \u00c7avu\u015fev, Mefkure Mollova, Niyazi H\u00fcseyinov, L\u00fctfi Demirov, Muharrem Tahsinov, Mehmet Bekirov, \u0130shak Ra\u015fidov, Nadiye Ahmedova, Sabahattin Bayramov, Halit Aliosmanov, Mehmet Sansarov, \u0130slam Beytullov, Ismail \u00c7avusev, Turhan Rasiev, Ismail Yakubov, Naci Ferhadov, Mukaddes Akmonova \u2013 Saidova, Yasar Gafur, Ali Boncuk, Ahmet Mehmedov, Isa Cebeciev, Mustafa Aladag, Ahmet Eminov, Ibrahim Kamberoglu, \u0130smail Bekirov, Mehmet Davudov, H\u00fcsmen \u0130smailov, Kaz\u0131m Memi\u015fev, \u0130smail \u0130bi\u015fev, Mehmet \u00c7avu\u015fev, Muhammet Yusufov, Yusuf Ahmedov, Recep K\u00fcp\u00e7\u00fcev, Nevzat Mehmedov, \u00d6mer Osmanov, Ali Bayramov, Latif Aliev, Mustafa Mutkov, Ali Kadirov, Halim Halilibrahimov, Faik \u0130smailov, Ali Pirov, Mustafa \u00c7etev, S\u00fcleyman Yusufov, Durhan Hasanov, Mehmet Memov, Nazmi Nuriev, Osman Azizov, Sabri \u0130brahimov, Ali Durmu\u015fev, Alis Saidov, Fehim \u015eent\u00fcrk, Fevzi Kadirov, Saban Mahmudov, Sahin Mustafaov, Latif Karag\u00f6z, Kadir Osmanov, Mustafa \u00d6mer Asi, Ahmet Aptiev, Necmiye Mehmedova, Lamia Varnal\u0131, Ahmet Aliev, Nevzat Yakubov, \u0130smet Bayramov, Nebiye \u0130brahimova, Ahmet Kadirov, Avni Veliev, Arzu Tahirova, Durhan Aliev, Saffet Eren, Emine Hocova, Aysel \u0130smailova S\u00fcleymanova, Kadriye Cesur, Nafize Habip, Naim Bako\u011flu, Beyhan Nalbantov, Ali Tiryaki, Fatma H\u00fcseyin<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kultur.gov.tr/TR/BelgeGoster.aspx?F6E10F8892433CFF8C37C091247A04E6157DD6E0CF8B4E79 |title=Bilgi |publisher=Kultur.gov.tr |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution of Turkish dialects in Bulgaria==\nThere are two main dialects; the first one is spoken in every area in south-east Bulgaria and is also used in the neighbouring countries (Greece and Turkey). It can be identified from the second one by looking at the \"present continuous time\"; it has the suffix forms ''-yirin, -yisin, -yiri''. In formal Turkish they are ''-yorum, -yorsun, -yor''. In the second dialect, used near Kurdzhali, the forms are; ''-v\u00e6rin, -v\u00e6sin, -v\u00e6ri''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ali Eminov |url=http://academic.wsc.edu/faculty/alemino1/biblios-turkish_language.html |title=Bibliographies-Turkish/Dialects in Bulgaria |publisher=Academic.wsc.edu |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref><ref>Salimehmed, Naylen; Bulgaristan K\u0131rcaali ili ve \u00e7evresi T\u00fcrk a\u011fz\u0131 [Turkish dialect of K\u0131rcaali province and its around], 2006 Edirne</ref>\n\n==Notable Bulgarian Turks==\n{{Further|List of Bulgarian Turks}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bulgarian Turks in Turkey]]\n*[[Crimean Tatars in Bulgaria]]\n*[[Islam in Bulgaria]]\n*[[List of Bulgarian Turks]]\n*[[Turkish minorities in the former Ottoman Empire]]\n*[[Turks in the Balkans]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Ahmet Erdi \u00d6zt\u00fcrk and Semiha S\u00f6zeri, \"[https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/politics-and-religion/article/diyanet-as-a-turkish-foreign-policy-tool-evidence-from-the-netherlands-and-bulgaria/67BCDC6BCF8A801E66CD5535DAB33CF1#fndtn-information Diyanet as a Turkish Foreign Policy Tool: Evidence from the Netherlands and Bulgaria]\", Politics and Religion, Volume 11, Issue, September 2018, pp.&nbsp;624\u2013648\n*Bulgarian Helsinki Committee, [https://web.archive.org/web/20090305152050/http://www.bghelsinki.org/special/en/2003_Muslims_fm.doc ''The Human Rights of Muslims in Bulgaria in Law and Politics since 1878''], 2003\n* [htt